<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="56" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1667]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,151,176]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Description.</emphasis>
Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[506,574,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1974,1996]" captionTargetBox="[159,1422,913,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1437,898,1950]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Trechisibus recuayi n. sp. HT: habitus (a); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view (b); median lobe of aedeagus in dorsal view (c)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/166622/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
a. Overall length of the HT 
<specimenCount box="[883,904,152,175]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
(from labrum to apex of elytra) 
<quantity box="[1270,1370,152,176]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.24" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" unit="mm" value="3.24">3.24 mm</quantity>
(PTT 
<specimenCount box="[151,193,189,212]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" type="female">♀♀</specimenCount>
<quantity box="[210,387,188,212]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.075" metricValueMax="3.17" metricValueMin="2.98" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" unit="mm" value="3.075" valueMax="3.17" valueMin="2.98">2.98–3.17 mm</quantity>
). Body dark brown, obovate, moderately shiny. Microsculpture in transverse meshes superficially impressed on elytra and on disc of pronotum, more visible near base and apex of pronotum and on head. Antennae, tibiae, clypeus and labrum reddish, femora a little darker; palpi yellowish. Brachypterous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1667]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Head moderately large, eyes small and scarcely convex; temples oblique and delicately pubescent, as long as eyes. Microsculpture markedly impressed over all surface but even stronger (almost wrinkled) near clypeus and towards eyes, laterally to frontal impressions, which are arcuate and deep. Clypeus with two apical setae on each side, the inner one shorter and thinner; labrum transverse, 6-setose, excavate at apex. Frons between eyes convex. Antennae slender, reaching the basal fifth of elytra.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1667]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
Pronotum moderately convex on disc, transverse (width/length = 1.38), with base wider than anterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[159,243,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 16" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1130,1153]" captionTargetBox="[201,1383,205,1107]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[191,1390,193,1119]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 16. Pronotum of Trechisibus: huascarani n. sp. HT (13); recuayi n. sp. HT (14); curtii n. sp. HT (15); lemairei n. sp. HT (16)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/166631/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). Disc shiny with very superficial microsculpture, which is distinct only near base and near front margin. Sides rounded in the fore half and subrectilinear in the basal half, shortly sinuate before base; basal margin excavate at middle and oblique near hind angles. Front angles scarcely prominent; hind angles marked, right or nearly obtuse. Mid longitudinal line distinctly impressed between the submarginal sulci. Lateral margins wide and broadened towards base; anterior and posterior margins bordered only at sides. Two lateral setae on each side, one at hind angles and one about 3/4 from base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1667]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Elytra oval (length/width=1.40), fairly convex and not depressed on disc. Microsculpture in transverse meshes, superficial in both sexes. Shoulders scarcely angulate with humeral angle distinct. The basal margin is interrupted in correspondence with the 6th interval. Scutellar stria absent. A juxtascutellar pore is present near base, in correspondence with the 2nd stria. Sides moderately rounded; lateral border narrow. One setigerous puncture on the 3rd stria at about 1/3 from base; preapical pore at about middle of the recurrent striole. Umbilicate series of 4+2+2 punctures, with the groups widely distanced from each other. 1st–5th striae very superficial and hardly visible, the others obliterated. Intervals flat. Elytral apex broad and rounded. The recurrent striola short and subrectilinear, without a remarkable apical carina.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1667]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Legs slender. Protibiae nearly straight and externally superficially furrowed. Tarsi pubescent on the upper side. The 1st and 2nd male protarsomeres asymmetrically dilated.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1667]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
Median lobe of aedeagus short and stout (
<figureCitation box="[674,742,1101,1126]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1974,1996]" captionTargetBox="[159,1422,913,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1437,898,1950]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Trechisibus recuayi n. sp. HT: habitus (a); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view (b); median lobe of aedeagus in dorsal view (c)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/166622/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
b), in lateral view the inferior edge delicately bent downward before apex, which is short and, in dorsal view, sinuate at sides and blunt (
<figureCitation box="[993,1063,1138,1163]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1974,1996]" captionTargetBox="[159,1422,913,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1437,898,1950]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Trechisibus recuayi n. sp. HT: habitus (a); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view (b); median lobe of aedeagus in dorsal view (c)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/166622/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
c). The internal armature is made by a robust copulatory piece with a dense cover of sclerotized teeth (
<figureCitation box="[931,1000,1173,1198]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1974,1996]" captionTargetBox="[159,1422,913,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1437,898,1950]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Trechisibus recuayi n. sp. HT: habitus (a); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view (b); median lobe of aedeagus in dorsal view (c)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/166622/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
b). Parameres narrow and long, almost equally long and longer than half of the median lobe, each provided with 3 apical setae (
<figureCitation box="[1140,1208,1210,1235]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1974,1996]" captionTargetBox="[159,1422,913,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1437,898,1950]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Trechisibus recuayi n. sp. HT: habitus (a); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view (b); median lobe of aedeagus in dorsal view (c)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/166622/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
b).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="56" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1667]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1245,1270]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Etymology</emphasis>
. Species name derived from the noun, in the genitive case, of the pre-columbian culture Recuay, that flourished in the Andean area of Cordillera Blanca from 200 BC to 600 AC.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="56" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1667]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,501,1317,1342]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
At present 
<taxonomicName box="[636,855,1317,1342]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Trechisibus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="recuayi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[636,855,1317,1342]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Trechisibus recuayi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[864,929,1317,1342]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[864,929,1317,1342]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is only recorded from the 
<typeStatus box="[1237,1285,1319,1343]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">type</typeStatus>
locality. The three specimens of the 
<typeStatus box="[408,456,1355,1379]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">type</typeStatus>
series were collected under stones laying on humid soil near a lake (about 4,550 meters a.s.l.) below the Punta Olímpica Pass, in a glacial area characterized by coarse detritic sediments (
<figureCitation box="[1243,1310,1389,1414]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1593,1615]" captionTargetBox="[340,1246,891,1571]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[340,1247,891,1572]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Peru, Dept. Ancash, Cordillera Blanca. The lagoon below the Punta Olímpica Pass (4,550 m a. s. l.) type locality of Trechisibus huascarani n. sp., as well as of Trechisibus recuayi n. sp. and Blennidus (Agraphoderus) huascarani Allegro, 2008." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/166621/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). It lives in syntopy with 
<taxonomicName box="[308,571,1426,1451]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Trechisibus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huascarani" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[308,571,1426,1451]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Trechisibus huascarani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[580,646,1426,1451]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[580,646,1426,1451]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Allegro, 2010" authorityName="Allegro" authorityYear="2010" box="[705,1311,1426,1451]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Blennidus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huascarani" subGenus="Agraphoderus">
<emphasis box="[705,817,1426,1451]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Blennidus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[836,996,1426,1451]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Agraphoderus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1014,1140,1426,1451]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">huascarani</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Allegro" box="[1150,1311,1426,1451]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" refString="Allegro, G. (2010) A peculiar new species of Blennidus Motschulsky subgenus Agraphoderus Bates from the Andes of the Cordillera Blanca (Peru) (Coleoptera: Carabidae: Pterostichini). Studies and Reports, Taxonomical Series, 6 (1 - 2), 1 - 7." type="journal article" year="2010">Allegro, 2010</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, which are recorded from the same 
<typeStatus box="[423,471,1463,1487]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1667]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,368,1498,1523]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Relationships.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[376,596,1498,1523]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Trechisibus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="recuayi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[376,596,1498,1523]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Trechisibus recuayi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[605,670,1498,1523]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[605,670,1498,1523]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is probably a close relative of 
<taxonomicName authority="Etonti &amp; Mateu, 1992" authorityName="Etonti &amp; Mateu" authorityYear="1992" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Trechisibus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamasi">
<emphasis box="[1028,1240,1498,1523]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Trechisibus lamasi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Etonti" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" refString="Etonti, M. &amp; Mateu, J. (1992) Sette nuovi Trechinae del Peru (Coleoptera, Carabidae). Bollettino del Museo civico di Storia naturale di Venezia, 41, 109 - 130." type="journal article" year="1992">Etonti &amp; Mateu, 1992</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Allegro, Giachino &amp; Sciaky, 2008" authorityName="Allegro, Giachino &amp; Sciaky" authorityYear="2008" box="[262,882,1533,1558]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Trechisibus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="decensii">
<emphasis box="[262,489,1533,1558]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Trechisibus decensii</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Allegro" box="[496,882,1533,1558]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" refString="Allegro, G., Giachino, P. M. &amp; Sciaky, R. (2008) Notes on some Trechini (Coleoptera Carabidae) of South America with description of new species from Chile, Ecuador and Peru. In: Giachino, P. M. (Ed.), Biodiversity of South America, I. Memoirs on Biodiversity 1. World Biodiversity Association Onlus, Verona, Italy, pp. 131 - 171." type="journal article" year="2008">Allegro, Giachino &amp; Sciaky, 2008</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, according to similarities in external morphology and in male genitalia (in particular all them have a hooked apex of the median lobe of aedeagus) (
<figureCitation box="[1276,1346,1570,1595]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[292,1275,213,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[272,1305,193,1948]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Median lobe of aedeagus of the ‘ Trechisibus lamasi group’ species: T. lamasi Etonti &amp; Mateu, 1992 (a); T. recuayi n. sp. HT (b); T. decensii Allegro, Giachino &amp; Sciaky, 2008 HT (c)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/256753/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). These species live in Cordillera Blanca, all inhabiting humid soils. Due to the marked similarities in male genitalia, they can be included in the ‘ 
<taxonomicName box="[413,515,1642,1667]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Trechisibus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamasi">
<emphasis box="[413,515,1642,1667]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">T. lamasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ species group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
